english:
  title: Preface to the Emended and Collated History of Goryeo
  author: Yun Hoe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The craft of history-writing is ancient indeed. It flourished in the age of Yao and Shun, as the records plainly show. When the historians of various kingdoms each preserved the events of their time, later compilers had something upon which to base their work. Consider how the Han founder, upon entering Guan, sent Xiao He to gather the records of Qin, and how the Tang emperor, upon ascending the throne, commanded Wei Zheng to compose the History of Sui—both sought to hold up the rise and fall of former ages as a mirror for later rulers, teaching them virtue and warning them of vice. Thus it is said: "Though a kingdom may perish, its history cannot." How can we doubt this truth?

    When our great founder established the dynasty, he commanded the Marquis of Fenghua, Jeong Do-jeon, and the Lord of Seowon, Jeong Chong, to compile the History of Goryeo. They gathered materials from the official records of each reign and consulted the chronicles of Minister Wen-ren Min Ji, the historical sketch of Minister Wen-chung Lee Je-hyeon, and the Golden Mirror Record of Minister Wen-jing Lee Saek. Weaving these together after the manner of Zuo's chronicle method, they completed their work in three years, producing thirty-seven scrolls. Yet the text contained numerous errors, and in the prefatory guidelines, matters from the reign of Wongjong onward bore the marks of presumptuous alteration.

    Our present majesty, possessed of keen intelligence and love of learning, devoted careful attention to the classics. Thus he commanded the Right Prime Minister Yu Gwan and the Chief Scholar of the Academy of Letters Byeon Gye-ryang to undertake a thorough review and correction of these errors. On the twenty-eighth day of the eleventh month of the twenty-first year of Yongle, Minister Yu submitted this memorial:

    "In the former dynasty, all rulers from the founder onward were given the title 'Zong'—a presumption. Yet Huizong and Dingjong are temple names, not personal titles. In the new history, these are altered to 'Huiwang' and 'Dingwang,' treating temple names as if they were posthumous names. This seems to deviate from truth. If we follow the official records, calling the founder 'Shengjing Wang' and Huizong 'Yigong Wang,' and recording all subsequent rulers by their true posthumous names, would we not preserve accuracy more faithfully?"

    That very day, as I attended the royal lecture, I received from the throne these words: "The Spring and Autumn Annals of Confucius borrowed the authority of the sovereign to establish the laws of one true king. When Wu and Chu presumed to claim the title 'king,' they were degraded and written as mere 'lords.' When the custom arose of sending gifts to funerals, the ruler was not styled 'heavenly king.' Thus Confucius rewrote and removed, added and subtracted, all by the discernment of a sage's heart. The historians of today, lacking insight into the sage's method of revision, should simply record facts as they are. Praise and blame will emerge naturally, and this suffices to establish credibility for later ages. There is no need to conceal the truth for the sake of earlier rulers, or carelessly to alter records and lose what is genuine.

    "Let the change from 'Zong' to 'Wang' follow the official records. Neither temple names nor posthumous names should be obscured. Let all revisions to the prefatory guidelines be made according to this principle."

    We officials, receiving this clear command, took the official records from Wongjong onward and compared them carefully with the new history. We made such corrections as changing 'Zong' to 'Wang,' 'festival day' to 'birthday,' 'edict' to 'instruction,' 'I' to 'we,' 'amnesty' to 'pardon,' 'empress dowager' to 'queen mother,' and 'crown prince' to 'heir apparent'—all restored to their original wording as found in the records of those times. The work of compilation being complete, the events are now largely whole and clear upon opening the pages, where encouragement and warning both reside.

    I reflect that Sima Qian, possessed of uncommon genius, gathered the documents from the stone chamber and composed the Records of the Grand Historian in one hundred thirty scrolls. His selections and rejections formed a unique school, yet still required Chu Shaosun to supplement what was lacking and Sima Zhen to correct its errors before the work became whole. If even Sima Qian required such aid, how much more so must lesser historians depend upon those who refine and correct their work? Thus the difficulty of writing history and the necessity of careful collation cannot be overstated. Your Majesty's foresight runs deep. The words spoken from the throne came from the sovereign's own judgment alone—so clear and just that no ordinary mind could fathom their full measure. I humbly bow and place these words before the scrolls as a record for all generations to come. Let those who read them pay careful heed.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The "History of Goryeo" (Goryeosa) was compiled by order of the Joseon founder, King Taejo, using materials from Goryeo's official records and previous historical works.
  - key: ''
    value: Yongle 21 (1423 CE) represents the date when this collation and correction project was completed under the reign of Joseon's third king, Sejong.
  - key: ''
    value: Sima Qian (司馬遷, c. 145-86 BCE) was China's greatest historian; his Records of the Grand Historian remains a foundational work of Chinese historiography.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Chu Shaosun and Sima Zhen illustrates how even masterworks of history require editorial refinement across generations.
